# Fast Local Map Pack Ranking System (5-Step Local SEO Framework)

*Source: local SEO practitioner outlining a 5-step system to move from invisible to top-3 in the map pack in ~2 weeks.*

---

## Core Idea: Google’s Local Algorithm Solves a Different Problem

Traditional SEO focuses on ranking web pages. Google’s **local algorithm** cares about something else:  

> “Can this business actually drive over and do the work for this searcher, in this area, and can it be trusted to do a good job?”

That means Google looks for three kinds of proof:

1. **Proof you’re a real business**  
2. **Proof you serve the area**  
3. **Proof other local entities recognize you**

If any of those are weak, you can sit at positions 4–10+ even with great content and tons of reviews.[web:82][web:85]

This framework focuses on five steps to feed those three proofs to Google quickly.

---

## Step 1 — Build the “Core 30” Service + Category Pages

Most local sites are either:

- tiny (5–6 generic pages), or  
- bloated with 200–400 low-value blog posts.

Neither structure tells Google clearly what you actually **do** and where.

The fix: build a **Core 30** set of pages that map tightly to your Google Business Profile (GBP):

- One page for **each primary category** on the GBP.
- One page for **each service** listed in GBP services.
- Each page’s title and H1 include:
  - the **exact GBP service/category phrase**, and  
  - the **city name**.

Example:

- GBP service: `Air conditioning repair`  
- Page title: `Air Conditioning Repair in Fort Wayne, IN | [Brand]`  

The point is not to spam keywords; it’s to make the mapping **unambiguous** so Google sees the website and the GBP “talking about the same thing,” which strengthens confidence you’re a real, relevant business for that intent.[web:79][web:81][web:82]

**Tooling pattern from the transcript:**

- Use a local rank tracking “heat map” tool (like LeadSnap) to see where you’re strong vs weak across the city.
- Use a browser extension (like GBP Everywhere) to pull all categories and services from the GBP.
- Use a crawler (Screaming Frog) to see what pages already exist and where gaps are.

This reveals:

- Missing category/service pages
- Mismatched titles vs GBP wording
- Thin or generic service coverage

---

## Step 2 — Use AI to Generate Locally-Relevant Service Content

Once the gaps are known, content must prove to Google that you are **actually local**, not a generic info site.

Difference in content intent:

- Not “what is HVAC?” blog posts.
- Instead, service pages that weave in:
  - local neighborhoods,
  - local weather patterns,
  - typical building types/codes,
  - local pain points (e.g., “Fort Wayne winters,” “Kansas City humidity”).

AI can draft this if it is **prompted with the right inputs**, such as:

- the specific service (e.g., “heating equipment supplier”),
- the exact city,
- the GBP categories and services,
- any important local details.

The transcript’s workflow:

- Crawl the site with Screaming Frog (free up to 500 URLs).
- Export internal URLs and link data.
- Feed the crawl data plus homepage content plus GBP categories/services into a strong LLM (e.g., Claude Sonnet/Opus).
- Use a robust prompt to:
  - audit structural gaps, and  
  - then generate new service/category pages that are locally targeted.

Key nuance: the AI is used **after** a structured crawl and GBP analysis, not instead of it, so the pages line up with the real site architecture and GBP.

---

## Step 3 — Back Each New Page With At Least One External Link

AI text alone is cheap and easy. Google can’t reliably “detect AI,” but it can detect **low-quality, unsupported content**.[web:94][web:98]

The missing ingredient for most agencies:

- They create lots of AI-generated pages.
- They do **not** give those pages any external validation.
- Google sees unlinked new URLs on a site and may treat them as low priority.

The method described:

- For every new service/category page, obtain **at least one decent external link**.
- Links don’t have to be extremely high-end, but they must be real and relevant enough to show the page isn’t orphaned AI slop.

In the transcript, that’s handled via a private network and a fulfillment site (icecreamtruck.shop) selling PBN links. From a strategic standpoint, the deeper lesson is:

> Each important new page should have at least one external signal pointing at it, so Google has reasons to crawl and value it.

If 806 Growth prefers, those could be:

- niche directories,  
- relevant blogs,  
- local partner sites,  
- or other non-spammy sources instead of PBNs.

---

## Step 4 — Build “Super Citations” That Are Hard to Fake

Typical local SEO citations:

- Easy, mass-submitted listings on common directories (Yelp, generic data aggregators).

“Super citations” in the video = listings that:

- Require verification,
- Sit inside major ecosystems (e.g., Bing Places, Apple Maps),
- Feed into car navigation systems, voice assistants, and other map providers.[web:82][web:85]

These matter because:

- They make your business show up in more **trusted local data sources**, not just cheap directories.
- They provide additional proof to both Google and AI tools (like ChatGPT when linked with browsing/search plugins) that you are a real, established local entity.

Workflow shown:

- Use a tool (again, LeadSnap in the transcript) that:
  - pulls GBP business details,
  - pushes consistent NAP data out to 50+ citation sources,
  - tracks status (live, submitted, updated).

Strategic takeaway:

- Ensure NAP consistency and verification across major map/search ecosystems, not just a long tail of low-trust directories.[web:79][web:81][web:82]

